\ fit-tree ( features y params -- tree ) — CART regression tree.
\ Numeric columns (vectors) split at a midpoint :threshold; categorical columns
\ (arrays) split on a mean-ordered subset stored as :categories. Every node
\ carries :prediction (mean of its rows) and :n_rows; an internal node adds
\ :feature and either :threshold or :categories plus :left and :right; a leaf
\ optionally carries :responses. Params frame: :max-depth (default unlimited),
\ :min-samples (minimum rows on each side of a split, default 1),
\ :store-leaf-responses (default off).

\ === numeric split at depth 1 ===
{ :x [ 1 2 3 4 ] vector } [ 1 1 5 5 ] vector { :max-depth 1 } fit-tree to tree
tree :prediction @ . cr             \ 3
tree :feature @ . cr                \ :x
tree :threshold @ . cr              \ 2.5
tree :n_rows @ . cr                 \ 4
tree /left/prediction @ . cr        \ 1
tree /right/prediction @ . cr       \ 5
tree /left/n_rows @ . cr            \ 2
clear

\ === max-depth 0 is a stump ===
{ :x [ 1 2 3 4 ] vector } [ 1 1 5 5 ] vector { :max-depth 0 } fit-tree to tree
tree :prediction @ . cr             \ 3
tree :feature has? . cr             \ 0
clear

\ === max-depth 2 deepens both sides ===
{ :x [ 1 2 3 4 5 6 7 8 ] vector } [ 1 1 2 2 8 8 9 9 ] vector { :max-depth 2 } fit-tree to tree
tree :threshold @ . cr              \ 4.5
tree /left/threshold @ . cr         \ 2.5
tree /right/threshold @ . cr        \ 6.5
tree /left/left/prediction @ . cr   \ 1
tree /right/right/prediction @ . cr \ 9
clear

\ === min-samples blocks a split that underfills a side ===
{ :x [ 1 2 3 4 ] vector } [ 1 1 5 5 ] vector { :min-samples 3 } fit-tree to tree
tree :feature has? . cr             \ 0
clear
{ :x [ 1 2 3 4 ] vector } [ 1 1 5 5 ] vector { :min-samples 2 } fit-tree to tree
tree :threshold @ . cr              \ 2.5
clear

\ === categorical split on a mean-ordered subset ===
{ :c [ :a :b :c :a :b :c ] } [ 1 10 2 1 10 2 ] vector { } fit-tree to tree
tree :feature @ . cr                \ :c
tree :categories @ . cr             \ < :c :a >
tree /left/prediction @ . cr        \ 1.5
tree /right/prediction @ . cr       \ 10
tree /right/n_rows @ . cr           \ 2
clear

\ === store-leaf-responses attaches :responses to leaves only ===
{ :x [ 1 2 3 4 ] vector } [ 1 1 5 5 ] vector { :max-depth 1 :store-leaf-responses 1 } fit-tree to tree
tree /left/responses @ . cr         \ 2x1 vector of 1 1
tree /left/responses has? . cr      \ 1
tree :responses has? . cr           \ 0
clear
{ :x [ 1 2 3 4 ] vector } [ 1 1 5 5 ] vector { :max-depth 1 } fit-tree to tree
tree /left/responses has? . cr      \ 0
clear

\ === best feature chosen across numeric and categorical ===
{ :x [ 1 2 3 4 ] vector :c [ :lo :hi :lo :hi ] } [ 1 9 1 9 ] vector { :max-depth 1 } fit-tree to tree
tree :feature @ . cr                \ :c
tree :categories @ . cr             \ < :lo >
tree /left/prediction @ . cr        \ 1
clear

\ === empty params default to unlimited depth ===
{ :x [ 1 2 3 4 ] vector } [ 1 2 3 4 ] vector { } fit-tree to tree
tree /left/feature has? . cr        \ 1
clear

\ === pfit-tree: parallel word, output matches fit-tree ===
{ :x [ 1 2 3 4 ] vector } [ 1 1 5 5 ] vector { :max-depth 1 } pfit-tree to tree
tree :threshold @ . cr              \ 2.5
tree /left/prediction @ . cr        \ 1
tree /right/prediction @ . cr       \ 5
clear
{ :c [ :a :b :c :a :b :c ] } [ 1 10 2 1 10 2 ] vector { } pfit-tree to tree
tree :categories @ . cr             \ < :c :a >
tree /left/prediction @ . cr        \ 1.5
tree /right/prediction @ . cr       \ 10
clear

\ === predict walks each row to a leaf ===
{ :x [ 1 2 3 4 ] vector } [ 1 1 5 5 ] vector { :max-depth 1 } fit-tree to tree
tree { :x [ 1 2 3 4 ] vector } predict matrix>array . cr  \ [ 1 1 5 5 ]
tree { :x [ 2 3 ] vector } predict matrix>array . cr      \ [ 1 5 ]  (<= 2.5 left)
clear
{ :c [ :a :b :c :a :b :c ] } [ 1 10 2 1 10 2 ] vector { } fit-tree to tree
tree { :c [ :a :b :c :z ] } predict matrix>array . cr     \ [ 1 10 2 10 ]  (:z unseen -> right)
clear
{ :x [ 1 2 3 4 ] vector } [ 1 1 5 5 ] vector { :max-depth 0 } fit-tree to tree
tree { :x [ 9 9 ] vector } predict matrix>array . cr      \ [ 3 3 ]  (stump -> root mean)
clear

\ === feature-importance: normalized impurity reduction per feature ===
{ :x [ 1 2 3 4 ] vector } [ 1 1 5 5 ] vector { :max-depth 1 } fit-tree to tree
tree feature-importance :x @ . cr                          \ 1  (only feature)
{ :a [ 0 0 1 1 ] :b [ 0 1 0 1 ] } [ 1 2 10 20 ] vector { :max-depth 2 } fit-tree to tree
tree feature-importance values vector sum . cr             \ 1  (normalized)
tree feature-importance :a @ 1000 * round 1000 / . cr      \ 0.783
tree feature-importance :b @ 1000 * round 1000 / . cr      \ 0.217
{ :x [ 1 2 3 4 ] vector } [ 1 1 5 5 ] vector { :max-depth 0 } fit-tree to tree
tree feature-importance keys size . cr                     \ 0  (stump, no splits)
clear

\ === missing values: a learned default direction per numeric split ===
\ non-missing x=1,2 -> y=1 and x=3,4 -> y=5; the two missing rows' response
\ decides which way a NaN goes, and predict on a NaN feature follows :default
{ :x [ 1 2 3 4 null null ] vector } [ 1 1 5 5 5 5 ] vector { :max-depth 1 } fit-tree to tree
tree :default @ . cr                                   \ :right  (missing y=5 matches right)
tree { :x [ null ] vector } predict matrix>array . cr  \ [ 5 ]
{ :x [ 1 2 3 4 null null ] vector } [ 1 1 5 5 1 1 ] vector { :max-depth 1 } fit-tree to tree
tree :default @ . cr                                   \ :left  (missing y=1 matches left)
tree { :x [ null ] vector } predict matrix>array . cr  \ [ 1 ]
{ :x [ 1 2 3 4 ] vector } [ 1 1 5 5 ] vector { :max-depth 1 } fit-tree :default has? . cr  \ 0  (no missing)
clear

\ === prune: cost-complexity collapse; prune-cv picks alpha by CV + 1-SE ===
{ :x [ 1 2 3 4 5 6 7 8 ] vector } [ 1 1 2 2 8 8 9 9 ] vector { :max-depth 2 } fit-tree 1000000 prune :feature has? . cr  \ 0  (huge alpha -> stump)
{ :x [ 1 2 3 4 5 6 7 8 ] vector } [ 1 1 2 2 8 8 9 9 ] vector { :max-depth 2 } fit-tree 10 prune /left/feature has? . cr    \ 0  (mid alpha -> sub-splits collapse)
\ signal in x1 (step at 4.5), x2 is noise; a depth-4 tree overfits, CV + 1-SE prunes to the real split
{ :x1 [ 1 2 3 4 5 6 7 8 ] vector :x2 [ 5 1 4 8 2 7 3 6 ] vector } [ 1 1 2 2 8 8 9 9 ] vector { :max-depth 4 :folds 4 } prune-cv to tree
tree :feature @ . tree :threshold @ . cr                                 \ :x1 4.5
tree /left/feature has? not  tree /right/feature has? not  and . cr      \ 1  (both children leaves)
clear

\ === draw-tree: indented split rules, left (condition-true) branch first ===
{ :x [ 1 2 3 4 5 6 7 8 ] vector } [ 1 1 2 2 8 8 9 9 ] vector { :max-depth 2 } fit-tree draw-tree
clear

\ === errors (reason parenthesized) ===
[ 1 2 ] vector [ 1 2 ] vector { } fit-tree          \ (features must be a frame)
clear
{ :x [ 1 2 ] vector } { } { } fit-tree              \ (response must be a numeric vector)
clear
{ :x [ 1 2 3 ] vector } [ 1 2 ] vector { } fit-tree \ (column and response lengths differ)
clear
{ :x < 1 2 > } [ 1 2 ] vector { } fit-tree          \ (column must be a numeric vector or an array)
clear
{ } [ 1 2 ] vector { } fit-tree                     \ (need at least one feature)
clear
